b\) Another analysis that could be run on this data is a one-way ANOVA to test how urchin gonad weight differs between experimental treatments. The response variable would be the gonad weight, which is a continuous quantitative variable. The predictor variable is the experimental treatment, which is a catagorical variable.

This analysis would answer the question how different treatments affect urchin gonad weight. The ANOVA will compare the means of a continuous response to a categorical predictor.

c\)

```{r}
#| message: false
#| warning: false
# Load package
library(car)

# Import dataset
urchins <- read_csv("urchin-experiment-data.csv")

# Clean dataset
urchins_clean <- urchins |>
  
  clean_names() |>
  
  select(experimental_treatment, weight_g) |>
  
  drop_na(weight_g) |>
  
  mutate(
    experimental_treatment = dplyr::recode(
      experimental_treatment,
      "c" = "Control",
      "n" = "Nutrient-enriched"
    )
  )

# Create QQ plots to assess normality
ggplot(urchins_clean,
       aes(sample = weight_g)) +
  
  stat_qq(color = "steelblue") +
  
  stat_qq_line(color = "darkred") +
  
  facet_wrap(~ experimental_treatment) +
  
  theme_classic()

# Test homogeneity of variance
leveneTest(
  weight_g ~ experimental_treatment,
  data = urchins_clean
)
# Run one-way ANOVA
urchin_anova <- aov(
  weight_g ~ experimental_treatment,
  data = urchins_clean
)

# Show ANOVA table
summary(urchin_anova)
```

